06914nmm a2200805Ia 9789633866580DE-B159720240328111612.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240328t20232023hu     fo  d z      eng d  a97896338665807 a10.1515/97896338665802doi  a(DE-B1597)664312  a(OCoLC)1384449269  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahucHU 7aPOL0420302bisacsh00aAnti-fascism in European History :bFrom the 1920s to Today /ced. by Jože Pirjevec, Sabrina P. Ramet, Egon Pelikan. 1aBudapest ;aNew York : bCentral European University Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (300 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies in Political Radicalization: Historical and Comparative Perspectives ;v100tFrontmatter -- tTable of contents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction: What is Anti-Fascism? Its values, its Strengths, its Diversities -- tPart One. Anti-Fascism in Fascist Italy's Borderlands -- t1. Hate Speech -- t2. Comparison of Fascist and National Defense Discourse -- t3. Fascism, Anti-fascism, and Ethnic Engineering in the Former Austrian Littoral -- t4. Persevering on the Ramparts of the Nation -- t5. The Anti-Fascism of Slovenian and Croatian Clergy in the Julian March during the Interwar Period - A View from the Vatican -- tPart Two: The Diversity of Anti-Fascism -- t6. The Anti-Fascism of Hans & Sophie Scholl -- t7. The Committee against Neofascism and Racial Prejudices -- t8. Anti-fascism in the Land of Holy Water Blessed by the Swastika -- t9. Mussolini, Vilfan, and the Slovenian Minority -- t10. From the Bauhaus to Buchenwald and to Berlin: Anti-fascism and Career in the Life of Franz Ehrlich -- tPart Three. Anti-Fascism as a Legitimating Ideology -- t11. Passing The Torch -- t12. Memory Practices in Slovenia Through the Lens of Public Opinion -- t13. A Note About the Collective Memory of Anti-Fascism Since World War Two and Its Revision -- t14. A Dire Warning to All Ethnic Minorities of Europe? -- t15. Maritime Communists Against Fascism and in Defense of the USSR -- tAfterword: "Are you a communist? No, I am an anti-fascist." -- tAbout the Contributors -- tFor Further Reading -- tIndex of Names0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2fd2star  aThe increasing radicalization of political life in most countries in Europe lends special relevance to studies of the antifascist legacies on the continent. This insightful collection of essays is an in-depth review of antifascism in Slovenia, setting it in the context of related movements elsewhere in Europe. The period treated by the 19 essays comprises the interwar period, World War Two, and the post-war decades. The comparative and transnational perspectives advanced by the volume change our understanding of antifascism. The essays deal with the right-wing but also left-wing instrumentalization of antifascism, with a particular focus on the communist and post-communist periods. The authors point out that antifascism comes in various strains, whether inspired by liberalism, social democracy, communism, monarchism, anarchism, or even Christian conservatism. The contributors bring to light several overlooked antifascist actors, campaigns, and organisations, mostly in Slovenia and the Adriatic area.  afunded by Opening the Future  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aAnti-fascist movementsy20th centuryzEurope. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Ideologies / Fascism & Totalitarianism.2bisacsh  aCentral Europe.  aFascism.  aanti-Fascism.1 aBraskén, Kasper, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCopsey, Nigel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCresciani, Gianfranco, 